{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17344570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17344570"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-27T07:30:32+09:30","options":[0],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-27T07:30:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1256612"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1256612"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538119"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1256612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1256612"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-27T07:28:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T04:50:21+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"new","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":1,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-27T07:30:32+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":1,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"16139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.12,0.16,0.06,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64078"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8830"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1028"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3018"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43612"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64078"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a new headache pattern. She has a long history of migraine with aura, currently managed with a CGRP monoclonal antibody (Eptinezumab). Her migraines typically present with visual aura followed by unilateral throbbing headache. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer past medical history also includes postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome and generalised anxiety disorder. Her medications include eptinezumab, escitalopram and propranolol. She works as an investment banker with frequent international travel. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe new headaches differ from her usual migraines, occurring two to three times weekly and accompanied by upper limb numbness, dizziness, and occasional speech difficulty lasting up to 24 hours. These symptoms persist even when her typical migraine pain resolves. She had a recent presentation to an emergency department, where it was suggested she had a diagnosis of functional neurological disorder (FND). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is normal with no focal deficits. Recent blood tests including full blood count, electrolytes, calcium/magnesium/phosphate and C-reactive protein are all within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI brain with contrast","Carotid doppler ultrasound","CT brain with contrast","Electroencephalogram","No further investigation required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several red flags that warrant further investigation: new headache pattern different from established migraines, prolonged neurological symptoms (\u0026gt;24 hours), and frequent international travel increasing risk of cerebral venous thrombosis. While functional neurological disorder may be present, organic pathology must first be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for new neurological symptoms in this context. It provides superior soft tissue resolution compared to CT and can detect subtle abnormalities including demyelination, small vessel disease, or early ischaemic changes. Contrast enhancement helps identify inflammatory processes, neoplasms, or venous thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the first investigation. While it can identify carotid stenosis, the patient\u0027s symptoms (prolonged neurological deficits, new headache pattern) are not typical for carotid disease. Additionally, her age makes significant carotid disease unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain with contrast i\u003C/strong\u003Es inferior to MRI for detecting posterior fossa lesions, subtle white matter changes, and early ischaemic changes. While appropriate in emergency settings, it is not the optimal choice for investigating subacute symptoms in an outpatient setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if seizures were suspected. The prolonged duration of symptoms (up to 24 hours) is not consistent with seizure activity, and there are no reported episodes of loss of consciousness or automatisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigation\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous. While the patient has risk factors for functional neurological disorder (anxiety, POTS), the presence of new neurological symptoms requires exclusion of organic pathology. The principle of \u0027functional does not equal fake\u0027 is important - patients can have both organic and functional symptoms simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["New neurological symptoms in a patient with known migraine require careful evaluation to exclude secondary causes.","Functional neurological disorders commonly co-exist with organic conditions like migraine.","MRI brain with contrast is the preferred imaging modality for investigating new neurological symptoms in migraine patients."],"references":["Espay AJ, Aybek S, Carson A, Edwards MJ, Goldstein LH, Hallett M, LaFaver K, LaFrance WC Jr, Lang AE, Nicholson T, Nielsen G, Reuber M, Voon V, Stone J, Morgante F. Current Concepts in Diagnosis and Treatment of Functional Neurological Disorders. JAMA Neurol. 2018 Sep 1;75(9):1132-1141. doi: 10.1001/jamaneurol.2018.1264. PMID: 29868890; PMCID: PMC7293766. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7293766/","Evans RW, Burch RC, Frishberg BM, Marmura MJ, Mechtler LL, Silberstein SD, Turner DP. Neuroimaging for migraine: the American Headache Society systematic review and evidence\u2010based guideline. Headache: The Journal of Head and Face Pain. 2020 Feb;60(2):318-36. Available online at ; https://ww.rwevansmd.com/EvansPublictations/neuroimaging%20for%20migraine%20the%20AHS%20systematic%20review%20and%20evidence%20based%20guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T21:58:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T21:59:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8830"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64078"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at